    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-05T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-05T18:00:00-05:00" n="304"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d304">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/5817a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-05T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 5, 1934—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. Press despatches from London report that Germany has reached agreement with
                    Great Britain whereby Germany will continue full interest service on Dawes and
                    Young loans, apparently abandoning its request for an arrangement for
                    “additional exports”. This will provoke strong reactions here unless similar
                    payments are extended to American holders. The circumstances under which these
                    loans were floated so largely in the United States for the benefit of the
                    European <pb facs="0477" n="377" xml:id="pg_377"/> situation and responsive to
                    requests of the principal European governments, including Germany, will make the
                    grant by Germany of any discrimination against American holders highly
                    objectionable here.</p>
                <p>Please inquire in the appropriate quarters as to German attitude in this
                    situation, and as to the intentions with respect to American bondholders.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
